VERDICT: not-confirmed
REASON: The ordering drift in src/sched.rs:446-469 is factually real — Rust's next_up_smp reads metairq_preempted in Step 4 before Step 5's update_metairq_preempt mutates it, while kernel/sched.c:253-268 evaluates the requeue predicate after the update. The PoC I appended to tests/sched_integration.rs reproduces and panics with "SC12 violated..." as predicted, and no Verus ensures clause pins the disjointness property, so the harness would produce a counter-example. The finding is NOT interesting, however, because next_up_smp has zero production callers: the live SMP scheduling decision is implemented by a C-inline copy of next_up in zephyr/gale_sched.c:211-305, and the FFI (ffi/src/lib.rs:5208-5327) only exposes gale_sched_next_up, gale_sched_should_preempt, and gale_k_sched_next_up_decide — the uniprocessor path — none of which invoke gale::sched::next_up_smp. Grep across src/, ffi/src/ and zephyr/ confirms next_up_smp appears solely in tests and model documentation. The report's "SC12" label also misrepresents the artifact requirement: SWREQ-SC-SC12 in artifacts/requirements.yaml:3244-3259 is "priority ordering preserved across run-queue operations," not the local src/sched.rs:387-388 comment about requeue conditions; the documented ASIL-D safety claim is untouched. Finally, artifacts/stpa.yaml:12-13 explicitly scopes UCAs out of the current artifact set and no safety/stpa/ucas.yaml exists, so there is no UCA surface to map to. This is a hygiene issue in verification-model code (missing Verus ensures and a misleading "ASIL-D verified properties: SC12" header comment) rather than a kernel-primitive bug on the verified production boundary. Recommend instead: either delete next_up_smp (it is dead code with respect to the C shim) or add the ensures clause and reorder Steps 4/5 to match kernel/sched.c, but do not file a UCA.
